  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here are some key examples:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) (Vienna Convention):** This convention was one of the first major international treaties to address money laundering. It required countries to criminalize the laundering of drug-related proceeds.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) (Palermo Convention):** This convention expanded the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include proceeds from other serious crimes, such as corruption, human trafficking, and arms smuggling.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003) (Merida Convention):** This convention focuses on combating corruption and includes provisions on preventing and criminalizing the laundering of proceeds of corruption.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty, the FATF Recommendations are the global standard for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and proliferation financing. They provide a comprehensive framework of measures that countries should implement. The FATF is an inter-governmental body, and its recommendations are widely adopted and implemented by countries around the world.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990):** This convention, also known as the Strasbourg Convention, focuses on international cooperation in combating money laundering, including measures related to asset tracing, seizure, and confiscation.\n\n*   **European Union Directives:** The European Union has issued several directives on money laundering that its member states are required to implement into their national laws. These directives have progressively strengthened the EU's anti-money laundering framework.\n\nThese are some of the most significant international legal instruments in the fight against money laundering. They establish standards for criminalizing money laundering, promoting international cooperation, and implementing preventive measures.",
